How To Scrape HTML Data In R

Herb Mueller

March 02, 2020

Scraping website data in R

In my own personal pre-R dark ages, there were times where I was tasked to manually transfer data from websites to excel documents for further analysis. These mind-numbingly long days must have had quite the impression on me because one of the first items I tried to teach myself in R was how to scrape data from websites. R has some incredibly in-depth data packages already available for download, but in our every day lives there may in instances when we need to create our own data sets to analyze. In this code-through, I will be explaining how to scrape data from websites using the “rvest” package.


Explaining “rvest”

Package “rvest” is used to easily scrape data from html web pages. By looking at the web site’s “page source” we can identify the items we would like to scrape from the website and easily save that information into a new data frame for our analysis.

Installing & Loading

In addition to installing the “rvest” package, I also installed and loaded the “XML2” package as it is required for some of the functions that you can run in “rvest”.

install.packages("rvest")
install.packages("xml2")

library(rvest)
library(xml2)

Check before you scrape

It is important to check the terms and conditions of the website before you scrape data from a specific website. Scraping data too often could get your IP address blocked by a website and using scraped data for profit may be illegal in some cases.


Scraping Website Data

We will start with the basics which is reading the html data. Below I have called the “read_html” function to read the HTML content from Reddit. I have assigned the html data to the object “Reddit”.

Reddit <- read_html ("https://www.reddit.com/")

With the data read, we can now begin scraping what we want from the website. For this exercise, we will scrape the thread names from Reddit’s front page. Before we begin though, we must investigate the website structure in determine how the data we are interested in is stored.

To do this, I right clicked on the first Reddit thread title and clicked “Inspect”. This informed me that the header class that Reddit thread titles are assigned to is “._eYtD2XCVieq6emjKBH3m”.

Alt text

Now that we know the header class for Reddit threads, we can use the function “html_nodes” to look for every header with this designation in the webpage. We can then use a pipe operator to feed the scraped Reddit threads into the “html_text” function to pull in the text from the scraped data.

Reddit %>%
  html_nodes("._eYtD2XCVieq6emjKBH3m") %>%
  html_text()
## [1] "There was a time not so long ago when we had to physically mail our funny videos to a television show and hope they choose to share it with viewers"
## [2] "Chris Matthews Out at MSNBC"                                                                                                                        
## [3] "Amy Klobuchar ends campaign for Democratic presidential nomination"                                                                                 
## [4] "\"You hit me! I was watching my screen and it didn't show any cars! I was signalling so I had right of way!\" -Actual quote from her"               
## [5] "If you grew up in 1930's Germany, you probably would have been a Nazi too."                                                                         
## [6] "#WarrenEndorseBernie Trends on Twitter as Centrist Democrats Rally Around Biden"                                                                    
## [7] "People that have a Carpeted Bathroom, why?"                                                                                                         
## [8] "Trending Communities"

As you can see, this is not a perfect system because the “Trending Communities” tab was also caught by this. However, this is still useful data that we can begin to assign to a data frame and track over a number of days, weeks, etc.


Scraping An HTML Table

Often times the data we would like to scrape from a website is contained within a table. “Rvest” makes scraping tables incredibly easy and allows us to easily transfer large data sets to R for us to perform our own analysis. We will once again start with simplying reading the HTML data from the website.

Premier_League_Stats <- read_html ("https://www.msn.com/en-us/Sports/soccer/premier-league/standings")

We could ask “rvest” to look for the table classes for us to scrape data using a similar method to the one above. If we run the “html_node” function and tell it to look for the nodeset “table” we will return the table class results for us to use.

Premier_League_Stats %>% 
  html_nodes("table")
## {xml_nodeset (1)}
## [1] <table class="tableview soccerfullstandings standing" summary="Standings" ...

Luckily, “rvest” has a function which allows us to easily scrape website tables in fewer steps. By using the “html_table” function, we can easily bring that table data from the website into R. Remember to assign “header” to True if the first row is a header or it will be included in your data. While this is great, we still need to save this as a data frame in order to start working with the data.

html_table(Premier_League_Stats, header=TRUE) -> Premier_League_Table

Using the “as.data.frame” function, we can now create a dataframe from the HTML data which will allow us to begin working with the data in R. From here the possibilies are almost endless.

Premier_League_Dataframe <- as.data.frame(Premier_League_Table)


Discussion

While my “rvest” examples may seem simple, the complexity of it can really begin to ramp up as you begin to tackle tougher challenges. What I have seen users do with the “rvest” package has really opened my eyes to what data analytic projects I could begin to tackle with this powerful tool at my disposal. I will leave below a few examples of what I have seen people use “rvest” to accomplish (with the addition of other packages as well).

  1. Scrapping multiple webpages at once
  2. Scrapping webpages at certain times of day
  3. Setting up email alerts based on scrapped data
